513
00:26:42.700 --> 00:26:44.870
forbad my tongue to speak ofMortimer.

514
00:26:44.870 --> 00:26:46.770
But I will find him when he liesasleep,

515
00:26:46.770 --> 00:26:48.930
and in his ear, I'll holla,"Mortimer!"

516
00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:51.200
Nay, I'll have a starling shallbe taught

517
00:26:51.200 --> 00:26:52.700
to speak nothing but "Mortimer"

518
00:26:52.700 --> 00:26:54.830
and give it him to keep hisanger still in motion.

519
00:26:54.830 --> 00:26:56.000
Hear you, cousin; a word.

520
00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:57.830
All studies here I solemnlydefy,

521
00:26:57.830 --> 00:27:00.670
save how to gall and pinch thisBolingbroke

522
00:27:00.670 --> 00:27:02.870
and that same sword-and-bucklerPrince of Wales.

523
00:27:02.870 --> 00:27:04.330
But that his father loves himnot

524
00:27:04.330 --> 00:27:06.300
and would be glad he met withsome mischance,

525
00:27:06.300 --> 00:27:08.030
I'd have him poison'd with a potof ale.

526
00:27:08.030 --> 00:27:09.600
Fare you well, kinsman.

527
00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:12.000
I'll talk to you when you'rebetter temper'd to attend.

528
00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.230
Why, what a wasp-stung andimpatient fool art thou

529
00:27:14.230 --> 00:27:15.930
to break into this woman's mood,

530
00:27:15.930 --> 00:27:18.070
tying thine ear to no tongue butthine own.

531
00:27:18.070 --> 00:27:20.330
Why, look you, I am whipp'd andscourged with rods,

532
00:27:20.330 --> 00:27:22.430
nettled and stung with pismires

533
00:27:22.430 --> 00:27:25.430
when I hear of this vilepolitician, Bolingbroke.

534
00:27:25.430 --> 00:27:28.830
In Richard's time-- what do youcall the place?

535
00:27:28.830 --> 00:27:30.770
A plague upon it; it is inGloucestershire.

536
00:27:30.770 --> 00:27:35.270
'Twas where the madcap duke hisuncle kept, his uncle York,

537
00:27:35.270 --> 00:27:37.700
where I first bow'd my knee untothis king of smiles,

538
00:27:37.700 --> 00:27:39.500
this Bolingbroke.

539
00:27:39.500 --> 00:27:41.570
'Sblood!

540
00:27:41.570 --> 00:27:43.570
When you and he came back fromRavenspurgh.

541
00:27:43.570 --> 00:27:45.600
At Berkley castle.

542
00:27:45.600 --> 00:27:47.370
You say true.

543
00:27:47.370 --> 00:27:49.870
Why, what a candy deal ofcourtesy

544
00:27:49.870 --> 00:27:52.130
this fawning greyhound then didproffer me.

545
00:27:52.130 --> 00:27:54.430
Look, "when his infant fortunecame to age,"

546
00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:57.630
And "gentle Harry Percy," and"kind cousin."

547
00:27:57.630 --> 00:28:00.070
Oh, the devil take suchcozeners!

548
00:28:03.570 --> 00:28:05.870
God forgive me.

549
00:28:05.870 --> 00:28:09.300
Good uncle, tell your tale.

550
00:28:11.270 --> 00:28:12.800
I have done.

551
00:28:12.800 --> 00:28:14.330
Nay, if you have not, to itagain.

552
00:28:14.330 --> 00:28:16.370
We will stay your leisure.

553
00:28:17.530 --> 00:28:19.730
I have done, i' faith!

554
00:28:19.730 --> 00:28:22.470
Then once more to your Scottishprisoners.

555
00:28:22.470 --> 00:28:26.170
Deliver them up without theirransom straight,

556
00:28:26.170 --> 00:28:29.200
and make the Douglas' son youronly mean

557
00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:30.600
for powers in Scotland,

558
00:28:30.600 --> 00:28:33.170
which, for divers reasons whichI shall send you written,

559
00:28:33.170 --> 00:28:35.030
be assured, shall easily begranted.

560
00:28:35.030 --> 00:28:36.300
You, my lord,

561
00:28:36.300 --> 00:28:38.170
your son in Scotland being thusemploy'd,

562
00:28:38.170 --> 00:28:39.800
shall secretly into the bosomcreep

563
00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:41.770
of that same noble prelate, thearchbishop.

564
00:28:41.770 --> 00:28:43.100
Of York, is it not?

565
00:28:43.100 --> 00:28:45.430
True, who bears hard hisbrother's death at Bristol,

566
00:28:45.430 --> 00:28:47.030
the Lord Scroop.

567
00:28:47.030 --> 00:28:50.630
I speak not this in estimation,as what I think might be,

568
00:28:50.630 --> 00:28:53.500
but what I know is ruminated,plotted, and set down

569
00:28:53.500 --> 00:28:55.130
and only stays but to behold theface

570
00:28:55.130 --> 00:28:56.900
of that occasion that shallbring it on.

571
00:28:56.900 --> 00:28:57.970
I smell it.

572
00:28:57.970 --> 00:28:59.270
Upon my life, it will do well.

573
00:28:59.270 --> 00:29:01.530
Before the game is afoot, thoustill let'st slip.

574
00:29:01.530 --> 00:29:03.400
Why, it cannot choose but be anoble plot.

575
00:29:03.400 --> 00:29:05.370
And then the power of Scotlandand of York

576
00:29:05.370 --> 00:29:07.870
to join with Mortimer, ha?

577
00:29:07.870 --> 00:29:09.330
And so they shall.

578
00:29:09.330 --> 00:29:11.770
Upon my life, it is exceedinglywell aim'd.

579
00:29:11.770 --> 00:29:13.530
And 'tis no little reason bidsus speed,

580
00:29:13.530 --> 00:29:15.200
to save our heads by raising ofa head,

581
00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:17.430
for, bear ourselves as even aswe can,

582
00:29:17.430 --> 00:29:19.200
the king will always think himin our debt

583
00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:21.130
and think we think ourselvesunsatisfied,

584
00:29:21.130 --> 00:29:22.870
till he hath found a time to payus home.

585
00:29:22.870 --> 00:29:24.370
And see already how he dothbegin

586
00:29:24.370 --> 00:29:26.200
to make us strangers to hislooks of love.

587
00:29:26.200 --> 00:29:28.400
He does. He does.

588
00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:30.300
We'll be revenged upon him.

589
00:29:30.300 --> 00:29:31.300
Cousin, farewell.

590
00:29:31.300 --> 00:29:32.600
No further go in this

591
00:29:32.600 --> 00:29:35.430
than I by letters shall directyour course.

592
00:29:35.430 --> 00:29:37.330
When time is ripe, which will besuddenly,

593
00:29:37.330 --> 00:29:39.270
I'll steal to Glendower and LordMortimer,

594
00:29:39.270 --> 00:29:41.230
where you and Douglas and ourpowers at once,

595
00:29:41.230 --> 00:29:43.000
as I will fashion it, shallhappily meet

596
00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:45.670
to bear our fortunes in our ownstrong arms,

597
00:29:45.670 --> 00:29:49.300
which now we hold at muchuncertainty.

598
00:29:49.300 --> 00:29:51.370
Farewell, good brother.

599
00:29:51.370 --> 00:29:53.330
We shall thrive, I trust.

600
00:29:55.430 --> 00:29:58.070
Uncle, adieu.

601
00:29:58.070 --> 00:29:59.300
Oh, let the hours be short

602
00:29:59.300 --> 00:30:04.630
till fields and blows and groansapplaud our sport.

603
